{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17505840","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17505840"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:36:42+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:36:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2490"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2490","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2490"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0.23,0.07,0.48,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2490"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"47272"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2490","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2490"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2490"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31983"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1249"},{"type":"tags","id":"1509"},{"type":"tags","id":"4183"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2236"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11549"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43168"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"47272","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/47272"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old man is referred to a nephrologist regarding persistent microscopic haematuria detected on a urine dipstick. He describes himself as very healthy and denies any recent infections or illnesses. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. His family history is unremarkable. His physical examination is unremarkable. Urine microscopy confirms haematuria with dysmorphic red cells on urinalysis.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Alport syndrome","Membranous nephropathy","Lupus nephritis","Thin basement membrane disease","Renal cell carcinoma"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EMicroscopic haematuria refers to blood only identifiable on urine dipstick or urinalysis, rather than the naked eye. Anatomically, it can be broadly classified as either glomerular or non-glomerular in origin, which is useful when considering the various underlying aetiologies. Glomerular haematuria is typically characterised by the appearance of dysmorphic red cells on urine microscopy (otherwise known as acanthocytes), along with red cell casts. The additional finding of proteinuria may be another sign of glomerular injury. Non-glomerular bleeding has a wide differential, the most common being persistent or recurrent urinary tract infections and the most sinister being urological malignancies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPersistent glomerular haematuria occurs in at least 1 % of the population. It is typically caused by \u003Cstrong\u003Ethin basement membrane disease \u003C/strong\u003Eor IgA nephropathy and less often due to \u003Cstrong\u003EAlport syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E. In this case, the cause of the haematuria is more likely to be due to thin basement membrane nephropathy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERenal biopsy is not necessary if the diagnosis can be made clinically, however is often considered particularly if there is evidence of progressive renal impairment. The prognosis is good and no treatment is necessary in most cases of thin basement membrane nephropathy, although some patients may benefit from the use of angiotensin-converting-enzyme inhibitor therapy to lower the intraglomerular pressure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe differentiation of Alport syndrome and thin basement membrane disease is important, as Alport syndrome will inevitably progress to end-stage renal failure although treatment is available to slow deterioration. Alport syndrome is typically characterised by haematuria and renal failure combined with hearing loss, lenticonus and retinal flecks. It is due to an abnormal composition of type 4 collagen with an autosomal or X-linked recessive inheritance. Therefore family history of Alport syndrome is important to elicit. Thin basement membrane nephropathy will present with isolated haematuria.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMembranous nephropathy\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents as a nephrotic syndrome (proteinuria without haematuria) whilst \u003Cstrong\u003Elupus nephritis \u003C/strong\u003Emost commonly affects young women, presents with both haematuria and proteinuria and may be associated with various extra-renal manifestations (including skin and joint).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhilst patients with \u003Cstrong\u003Erenal cell carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E may have microscopic haematuria, the red cells would not be dysmorphic.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Thin basement membrane disease is an important cause of persistent glomerular haematuria, but is not of concern."],"references":["Savige J, Gregory M, Gross O, Kashtan C, Ding J, Flinter F. Expert guidelines for the management of Alport syndrome and thin basement membrane nephropathy. J Am Soc Nephrol. 2013;24(3):364-75. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/23349312/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31983"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2490"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31983","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/31983"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-06-19T16:26:32+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-06-19T16:26:33+09:30"},"relationsh